"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638397","Home Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>There is always a presumption of liberty and detention is only ever used sparingly and for the shortest period necessary. For those individuals with no right to remain in the UK, we expect them to leave the country of their own volition and the Home Office has programmes to support voluntary return.</p><p>The Home Office expects that current and planned reforms, and broader changes in legislation, policy and operational approaches will lead to a reduction in the number of the most vulnerable detained and the duration of detention before removal.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","53576","2017-04-20T08:29:16.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638397/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638397/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what community-based alternatives to detention her Department developed and implemented as a result of the report by the All Party Parliamentary Group on Refugees and the All Party Parliamentary Group on Migration, published in March 2015, and the report by Stephen Shaw, Review into the Welfare in Detention of Vulnerable Persons, Cm 9186, published in January 2016.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","53631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638398","Home Office","false","2016-11-22","<p>Internal consultation has taken place on Immigration and Enforcement’s 2016/17 business plan and it will be published in due course. External consultation does not routinely take place on the business plan document.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-22T17:14:49.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638398/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638398/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Immigration Enforcement Directorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what consultation is taking place to prepare her Department's Immigration and Enforcement Business Plan 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","53635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638399","Home Office","true","2016-12-21","<p>The Home Office is responsible for the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002. The powers in the Proceeds of Crime Act may be exercised by law enforcement agencies such as the NCA, SFO, constables and HMRC. <ins class="ministerial">It is Home Office policy not to comment on individual cases. </ins></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-12-21T12:29:16.25Z","2016-12-21T16:12:02.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638399/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638399/answer","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638399/answer/previousversion/28177","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Freezing of Assets: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has subjected (a) Dimitry Klyuev, (b) Pavel Karpov or (c) Andrey Pavlov to an (i) asset freeze or (ii) asset recovery in the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","53636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638400","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-20","<p>Assessments of the likely equality impacts and of the potential economic costs and benefits of provision for marriages by non-religious belief organisations, including humanist marriages, were published on gov.uk in June 2014 in the consultation paper on such provision.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-20T16:45:34.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638400/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638400/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-17","Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of granting legal recognition to humanist marriages.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","53653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638401","Home Office","false","2016-11-24","<p>All permanent members of staff directly employed by the Home Office and its agencies are paid the Living Wage Foundation rates or above. The Home Office and its agencies do not retain any directly employed staff on zero-hour contracts.</p><p>All temporary agency staff are employed in accordance with the Agency Workers Regulations which ensures parity with directly employed staff after 12 weeks. Starting pay rates comply with the requirements of the current Government Living Wage legislation; this is a contractual obligation on the supplier and is monitored through contract compliance mechanisms.</p><p>The Home Office only requires its outsourced contractors to comply with the legal minimum standards of pay of their staff as set out in the Government National Living Wage legislation; again this is a contractual obligation on the supplier and is monitored through contract compliance mechanisms and annually through our supplier assurance programme. The Home Office does not however require outsourced contractors to pay the Living Wage Foundation rates or requires or monitors that such outsourced contractors do not employ staff on zero hours contracts.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-24T18:32:58.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638401/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638401/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Home Office: Liverpool City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people working for her Department or its executive agencies in the Liverpool City Region on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wages Foundation; and how many such people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","53674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638402","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-11-28","<p>The House of Commons Commission does not hold such information as it is the House of Lords which has always been responsible for the production of record copies of Acts. In his letter of 17 September 2015 to the Administration Committee, the then House of Lords Chairman of Committees said that “Between 2009/10 and 2014/15 the cost to the Lords of producing vellums averaged slightly over £100,000 per year”.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-11-28T16:42:43.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638402/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638402/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-11-17","Acts: Publishing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what information the Commission holds on the cost per page of printing bills on vellum in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","53503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638403","Department for International Development","true","2016-11-22","<p>As the answer to Question 907180 states, no structures directly funded by the UK <ins class="ministerial">in recent years </ins>have been demolished. Since 2009 approximately 180 structures funded by the European Union’s Humanitarian Aid and Civil Protection Office (ECHO) have been demolished or confiscated. The UK regularly raises its concerns about demolitions with the Government of Israel.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-22T15:37:58.49Z","2017-02-08T14:56:14.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638403/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638403/answer","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638403/answer/previousversion/21862","Biography information for Rory Stewart","20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-17","Occupied Territories: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2016 to Question 907180, on occupied territories: demolition, how many structures built with some financial assistance from the UK have been demolished by the Israeli government; and how much UK funding was provided for those structures.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","53572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638404","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-22","<p>DFID has provided emergency cash transfers to more than 12,000 households and vaccinated three million livestock. We are currently providing 16,000 households with food, child nutrition support, access to health care, clean water and shelter. Our most recent funding, released this month, will provide cash to a further 6,500 households and nutrition and water for a further 50,000 people.</p><p>We are closely monitoring the effects of the drought, and matching our own substantial contribution with a campaign to encourage other international partners to step up and do more.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-22T14:16:43.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638404/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638404/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-17","Somalia: Droughts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance her Department is giving to the regions of Somaliland and Somalia experiencing drought.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","53640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638405","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-25","<p>Victims deserve the best possible support to help them cope with what they have been through and recover as much as possible.</p><p> </p><p>That is why we have protected the victims' budget and given PCCs the flexibility to decide which services are needed in their local area.</p><p> </p><p>Also under the revised Victims' Code published in 2015, victims of all criminal offences are now entitled to support from a wide range of organisations.</p><p> </p><p>The Victims’ Code is a statutory code of practice. It sets out the services to be provided to victims of crime, including how to complain if they are dissatisfied. Service providers are required to comply with the code. Part of the role of the Commissioner for Victims and Witnesses is to keep under review the operation of the Code.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice requires Police and Crime Commissioners, as part of the monitoring of grant agreements for the delivery of local services for victims, to confirm they are compliant with the Code.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","53561","2016-11-25T14:34:20.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638405/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638405/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-17","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what performance data her Department has (a) requested and (b) received from criminal justice agencies on their levels of compliance with the Code of Practice for Victims of Crime in each of the last two years; and if she will publish that data.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","53621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638406","Home Office","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Government plans to publish a refreshed version of the 2011 Missing Children and Adults Strategy early next year.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-23T16:44:41.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638406/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638406/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-17","Missing Persons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish the next review of the Missing Children and Adults strategy.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","53624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638407","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-08","<p>The table below shows the number of staff directly employed by the Department or its executive agencies who are paid less than the living wage (LW) as defined by the Living Wage Foundation, none of which are employed on zero hours contracts. This data is shown as at 30<sup>th</sup> September 2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number below living wage</p></td><td><p>Total headcount in Liverpool region</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MoJ inc MoJ HQ, HMCTS, OPG, CICA and LAA.</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>618</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NOMS (including the National Probation Service)</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>834</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The MoJ contractors supplying the provision of Contingent Labour Services have confirmed that 27 agency staff are paid less than the Living Wage in the Liverpool City Region.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-12-08T14:47:03.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638407/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/638407/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-17","Ministry of Justice: Liverpool City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people working for her Department or its executive agencies in the Liverpool City Region on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wages Foundation; and how many such people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","53672"
